The experimental Al–3Ti–0.75C alloy was produced at Marmara Research Center. Al–10Ti melt was first diluted to a Ti level of 3% and was then treated with a specially designed graphite rotor to establish a chemical reaction between the titanium dissolved in molten aluminium and solid carbon at the surface of the graphite rotor. Under the conditions described in ref. [23], it took about 20min to fully convert the Ti in the melt into TiC. The experimental Al–3Ti–0.75C alloy thus obtained was essentially an Al–TiC composite with a dispersion of TiC particles embedded in the aluminium matrix (Fig. 1
). This is evidenced by the XRD scan which reveals only the Bragg peaks for the TiC phase, in addition to those of the aluminium matrix (Fig. 2
). Several soluble Al3Ti particles, tolerated to avoid the formation of the Al4C3 phase during processing, were also noted. The Al3Ti particles, however, were very few and very small to generate a detectable signal in the XRD scan.

The stoichiometric Al–TiC alloy thus obtained was mixed with a commercial Al–10Ti alloy (Fig. 3
) and commercial purity (99.7%) aluminium so as to obtain a series of grain refiner samples with the Ti concentration fixed at 3wt.% but with different C contents ranging from 0.75 to 0.15%. Finally, the Al–10Ti alloy was diluted with a commercial purity aluminium ingot to obtain an Al–3Ti grain refiner sample, with only the soluble aluminide particles. Consequently, five different grain refiner samples where the insoluble TiC and soluble Al3Ti particles were sourced from the same Al–3Ti–0.75C and Al–10Ti alloys, respectively, were obtained (Table 1
). The five different grain refiner samples were then assessed for their grain refining performances.
